title: For Sale:  BLAST FROM THE PAST - BERETTA MOD. 950BS JETFIRE IN .25 ACP. **FINAL REDUCTION**
postcontent: Beretta Mod. 950BS in .25 ACP. - Private sale of an older classic Beretta in good condition. Made in Italy. When I called Beretta, they advised the gun's serial number predates their record keeping, and that based upon its features it had to have been manufactured sometime between 1950 and 1959. Bore is in excellent shape. I don't think it was shot much. Has a tip up barrel. Perfect gun for someone that is disabled, or has difficulty racking a slide. You never rack the slide to shot this gun. You just drop a round in the tip up barrel, and once fired, it automatically cycles the next round. For a “mouse” gun, it has a large 8+1 capacity. The Beretta is only single action, (where the hammer resets due to the blowback from the fired cartridge, and not from pulling the trigger – The trigger only releases the hammer, which equals a light and smooth trigger). Very nice aged look. Nice, and small for concealed carry. Carry it with Hornady “magic” bullets, and it will be just as effective as a 40 caliber. I already have two (2) good shooting .25 acp caliber guns, and can't really justify keeping this one. Own a classic Beretta for only $155 (reduced). Private sale. title: For Sale:  Remington 700 .30-06 Synthetic w/ Extras
postcontent:
Selling my beloved 700!  Hate to see her go, but tuition fees and book costs are starting to stack up... have to prioritize, and unfortunately, I can no longer afford shooting/hunting/collecting weapons any longer.  

What you get:
Rifle: Remington 700
Caliber: .30-06 Springfield
Stock: Synthetic All-Weather
Optics: Burris Fullfield II 3x9-40
Reticle: Ballistic Plex
Ammo: 10 Rounds Remington Core Lokt & 10 Rounds Nosler Accubond
Extras: Neoprene Sling & Buttstock Ammo Sleeve

The ammo is worth about $30, the optic is worth about $215 (with rings and base), the sling is worth $20 and the sleeve is worth $10.  So you are basically getting the rifle for $155.  Not a bad deal in my book.

Just as a side note, when I purchased this rifle, I had been considering a few other rifles.  Primarily the 7mm Rem Mag, 300 Win Mag & the .308.  I ended up going with the .30-06 for a few reasons.  First is history.  My grandfather shot a .30-06, my daddy still shoots a .30-06 so it seemed fitting that I shoot one, too.  The cost of the magnums (both the rifle, and the ammo) pretty much ruled those out.  I purchased the rifle primarily for bear and the occasional deer.  My buddies thought I was crazy to bring a non-magnum into the field to kill a bear.  Turns out that bears don't know the difference.  I shot this 300 pound boar at just over 150 yards with 180 grain Corelokts and he dropped like a rock.

With practice, you can effectively harvest any animal within the United States with ease.

If interested, please email or text at REDACTED.

Thank you for looking and god bless.
